[{"id":41705,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8cb9ce9a-72ba-4b3f-8f81-e25c10734098-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 139px;\" /></p><p>Emf produced is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><msub><mi>L</mi><mo>&#8869;</mo></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mo>&#8869;</mo></msub></math></p><p>We know&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>, so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p>Then,&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>20</mn></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41732,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$2 \\mathrm{~mA}$","$1 \\mathrm{~mA}$","$40 \\mu \\mathrm{A}$","$20 \\mu \\mathrm{A}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Given Number of turns, $\\mathrm{n}=1000$ turns $/ \\mathrm{cm}=1000 \\times 100$ turns $/ \\mathrm{m}$ Coercivity of ferromagnet, $\\mathrm{H}=100 \\mathrm{~A} / \\mathrm{m}$ Current to demagnetise the ferromagnet, $\\mathrm{I}=?$\nUsing, $\\mathrm{H}=\\mathrm{nI}$\nor, $\\quad 100=10^5 \\times \\mathrm{I}$\n$\\therefore \\quad \\mathrm{I}=\\frac{100}{10^5}=1 \\mathrm{~mA}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":41731,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math><mn>285&nbsp;</mn><mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mrow></math>","<math><mn>2600&nbsp;</mn><mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mrow></math>","<math><mn>520&nbsp;</mn><mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mrow></math>","<math><mn>1200&nbsp;</mn><mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mrow></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Coercivity <math><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0.2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5.2</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mrow></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2600</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>A</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>m</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41703,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d101280d-3230-4629-8579-8e3362dc1b41-image.png\" style=\"width: 327px; height: 220px;\" /></p><p>Angle of dip,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p>Angle of dip or magnetic dip is the angle the net earth&#39;s magnetic field and it&#39;s horizontal component.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#948;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#948;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Magnetic field,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac bevelled=\"true\"><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac bevelled=\"true\"><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac bevelled=\"true\"><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41721,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>m</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>According to Curie&#39;s Law,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#967;</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>T</mi></mfrac></math><br />Therefore,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math><br />Also,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#967;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>M</mi><mi>B</mi></mfrac></math><br />So,&nbsp;<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></math><br />On substituting the values,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Therefore,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41713,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["True dip is not mathematically related to apparent dip.","True dip is less than apparent dip.","True dip is always greater than the apparent dip.","True dip is always equal to apparent dip."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>If&nbsp;the apparent dip circle is at an angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi></math>&nbsp;with true dip circle then,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/11ac7fc1-12b6-4947-bd46-b6fc87302962-D780.png\" style=\"width: 284px; height: 401px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>'</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>tan</mi><mfenced><mi>&#981;</mi></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>&#981;</mi></math></p><p>Therefore, apparent dip angle is greater than true dip angle.</p><p>Hence, true dip <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is less than apparent dip&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msup><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msup></mfenced></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41720,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["have no relation with external magnetic field.","decrease in size and changes orientation.","increase in size but no change in orientation.","may increase or decrease in size and change its orientation."],"answer":3,"solution":"Soft ferromagnetic materials are materials which can be easily magnetised and demagnetised by external magnetic field. When external field is applied, the domains experiences a net torque hence change its orientation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41712,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["Statement I is true but Statement II is false.","Both Statement I and Statement II are true.","Both Statement I and Statement II are false.","Statement I&nbsp;is false but Statement II is true."],"answer":0,"solution":"As temperature increases, domains disintegrate so ferromagnetism decreases and above curie temperature it become paramagnet.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41714,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfrac><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mi>tan&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>tan&#948;</mi><mo>'</mo></msup><mi>cos&#952;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41740,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{A} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{D}, \\mathrm{B} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{P}, \\mathrm{C} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{F}$","$\\mathrm{A} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{F}, \\mathrm{B} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{D}, \\mathrm{C} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{P}$","$\\mathrm{A} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{P}, \\mathrm{B} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{F}, \\mathrm{C} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{D}$","$\\mathrm{A} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{F}, \\mathrm{B} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{P}, \\mathrm{C} \\leftrightarrow \\mathrm{D}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Diamagnetic materials are repelled in an external magnetic field.\nBar $B$ represents diamagnetic materials.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41727,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math><mn>3.726</mn><mo>x</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>2.672</mn><mo>x</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>3.267</mn><mo>x</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>3.672</mn><mo>x</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>From Curie&#39;s law, the magnetic susceptibility is inversely proportional to the temperature, i.e.,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#967;</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>T</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>Hence, the ratio of magnetic susceptibility at different temperature&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>350</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>350</mn><mn>300</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>267</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41678,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Let the magnetic moment of each magnet be $M = 3\\sqrt{5}$ J/T.<br><br>The distance of point P from the center of each magnet is $r = 5$ cm $= 0.05$ m.<br><br>For the first magnet (horizontal), point P lies on its axial line. The magnetic field at P due to the first magnet is:<br><br>$B_1 = \\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{2M}{r^3}$<br><br>The direction of $\\vec{B}_1$ is along the axis of the first magnet.<br><br>For the second magnet (vertical), point P lies on its equatorial line. The magnetic field at P due to the second magnet is:<br><br>$B_2 = \\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{M}{r^3}$<br><br>The direction of $\\vec{B}_2$ is parallel to the axis of the second magnet, which is perpendicular to the axis of the first magnet.<br><br>Since $\\vec{B}_1$ and $\\vec{B}_2$ are perpendicular to each other, the net magnetic field at P is:<br><br>$B = \\sqrt{B_1^2 + B_2^2}$<br><br>Substituting the expressions for $B_1$ and $B_2$:<br><br>$B = \\sqrt{\\left(\\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{2M}{r^3}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{M}{r^3}\\right)^2}$<br><br>$B = \\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{M}{r^3} \\sqrt{2^2 + 1^2} = \\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{\\sqrt{5}M}{r^3}$<br><br>Substituting the given values $\\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} = 10^{-7}$ T m/A, $M = 3\\sqrt{5}$ J/T, and $r = 0.05$ m:<br><br>$B = 10^{-7} \\times \\dfrac{\\sqrt{5} \\times 3\\sqrt{5}}{(0.05)^3}$<br><br>$B = 10^{-7} \\times \\dfrac{15}{125 \\times 10^{-6}}$<br><br>$B = \\dfrac{15 \\times 10^{-1}}{125}$<br><br>$B = 0.1 \\times 0.12$ T<br><br>$B = 0.012$ T<br><br>$B = 12 \\times 10^{-3}$ T<br><br>Comparing this with the given value $\\alpha \\times 10^{-3}$ T, we get $\\alpha = 12$.<br><br>Answer: $12$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41701,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><msqrt><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msqrt></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><msqrt><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msqrt></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><msqrt><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msqrt></mfenced></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Given here, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#39;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;and apparent value of dip, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.</p><p>If <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi></math> is horizontal component of earth&#39;s magnetic field in magnetic meridian, then&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><msup><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mi>H</mi></mfrac></math>.</p><p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>H</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;be component of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi></math>&nbsp;at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;to magnetic meridian, then&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><msub><mi>H</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mrow><mi>H</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#945;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>tan</mi><msup><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#945;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>tan</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math></p><p>Thus, the actual value of the angle of dip is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msqrt><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msqrt></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41743,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["30 mA","60 mA","3 A","6 A"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>For solenoid, the magnetic field needed to be magnetised the magnet.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>n</mi><mi>I</mi></math></p><p>where, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>100</mn><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>I</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":41747,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$4 \\times 10^{-8}$ tesla","$3.5 \\times 10^{-8}$ tesla","$5 \\times 10^{-8}$ tesla","$3 \\times 10^{-8}$ tesla"],"answer":2,"solution":"Along the equatorial line, magnetic field strength\n$$\n\\left.B=\\frac{\\mu_0}{4 \\pi} \\frac{M}{\\left(r^2+\\ell^2{ }^{3 / 2}\\right.}\\right)\n$$\nGiven: $M=4 \\mathrm{~J} T^{-1}$\n$$\nr=200 \\mathrm{~cm}=2 \\mathrm{~m}\n$$\n$\\ell=\\frac{6 \\mathrm{~cm}}{2}=3 \\mathrm{~cm}=3 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~m}$\n$$\n\\therefore B=\\frac{4 \\pi \\times 10^{-7}}{4 \\pi} \\times \\frac{4}{\\left[2^2+\\left(3 \\times 10^{-2}\\right)^2\\right]^{3 / 2}}\n$$\nSolving we get, $B=5 \\times 10^{-8}$ tesla","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":41708,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["low coercivity and high retentivity.","low coercivity and low permeability.","high permeability and low retentivity.","high permeability and high retentivity."],"answer":2,"solution":"Electromagnets are made of soft iron because of its high permeability and low retentivity. High permeability&nbsp;means that the core provides complete linkage of magnetic flux of the primary coil to the secondary coil.&nbsp;&nbsp;The determination of the magnetism left in the material after the removal of the magnetizing field is known as retentivity. The required condition for the operation of electromagnets is the fast reversal of polarity, so high retentivity is undesirable. So, soft iron core has high permeability and low retentivity.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41736,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;for transformers and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math></p><p>for electric generators.</p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&nbsp;for electromagnets and transformers.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;for electric generators and transformers.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;for electromagnets and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math> for electric generators."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>As we know that, area of&nbsp;Hysteresis loop represents the net loss of energy&nbsp;by the material per unit volume,taken over complete cycle.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d8351c41-e7db-42cd-8a5f-6d86920cd3e7-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 223px;\" /><br />Graph <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;is hard ferromagnetic material substance as the area of the loop is more, hence the hysteresis loss will be more and thus the value of coercivity will be high which are best suited to use as Permanent Magnet<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f2d12aad-bfdc-4da9-a7ab-a04b96dbc02a-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 218px;\" /><br />Graph <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&nbsp;is graph of soft ferromagnetic material substance as the area of the loop is less and hence the hysterisis loss will be less which is required condition for transformer. And the value of coercivity will be low too.</p><p>Hence this material are best suited to use as Electromagnets and Transformer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":41679,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["(A) is true but (R) is false","Both (A) and (R) are true but (R) is not the correct explanation of (A)","(A) is false but (R) is true","Both (A) and (R) are true and (R) is the correct explanation of (A)"],"answer":1,"solution":"Assertion (A) states that individual atoms in a ferromagnetic material possess a magnetic dipole moment and interact to form domains. This is a correct description of the domain theory of ferromagnetism, where exchange interactions lead to spontaneous alignment of moments within small regions called domains.<br>Reason (R) states that at high temperatures (above the Curie temperature $T_C$), the domain structure disintegrates due to thermal agitation, and the material becomes paramagnetic. This is also a correct statement regarding the temperature dependence of ferromagnetic materials.<br>However, Reason (R) describes the effect of temperature on the domain structure, whereas Assertion (A) describes the fundamental nature and formation of domains in the ferromagnetic state. The disintegration of domains at high temperature is not the reason why they form spontaneously at lower temperatures. Therefore, both statements are true, but (R) is not the correct explanation of (A).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41746,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.50</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>.80</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.6</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.56</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EM0010402_AnsExp4_1.jpg\" /><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mtext>net</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mn>1</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mn>H</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math><mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mi>μ</mi> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> <mi>π</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>M</mtext> <mn>1</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>x</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mi>μ</mi> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> <mi>π</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>M</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>x</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <msub><mtext>B</mtext> <mtext>H</mtext> </msub></mrow></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mrow><mo>{</mo> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mn>10</mn></mrow> <mrow> <mo>−</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow> </msup> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>1.2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> <mo>}</mo></mrow></mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>0.1</mn></mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo><mn>3.6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup> <mrow> <mn>10</mn></mrow> <mrow> <mo>−</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>2.56</mtext> <mo>×</mo> <msup> <mtext>10</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mtext>&nbsp;Wb</mtext> <mo>/</mo> <msup> <mtext>m</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":41718,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>108</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>54</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>88</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>37</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>62</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8712;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mover><mi>V</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mover><mi>L</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi><mi>L</mi><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#952;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>180</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi>sin</mi><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>108</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41722,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>J</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>J</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>J</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>11</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>J</mtext></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#964;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>MBsin&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>018</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.018</mo></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.018</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.06</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.5</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.64</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>A</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#916;U</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>MB</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>180</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>MB</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cos</mi><msup><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>MB</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.6</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.06</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>072</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41739,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>&#8800;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi>B</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"In diamagnetic material, the magnetic field strength decreases. So, in a perfect diamagnetic,&nbsp;it has to be zero.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41754,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$\\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~W}$","W","$\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\mathrm{~W}$","$2 \\mathrm{~W}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\tau=(\\mathrm{H}) \\tan 60^{\\circ} \\quad=\\mathrm{W} \\cdot \\sqrt{3}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":41698,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["to oscillate the coil in magnetic field for longer period of time","to bring the coil to rest quickly","&nbsp;to produce large deflecting torque on the coil","to make the magnetic field radial"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Certain galvanometers have a fixed core made of nonmagnetic metallic material. When the coil oscillates, the eddy currents generated in the core oppose the motion and bring the coil to rest quickly.&nbsp;Eddy currents are loops of electrical current induced within conductors by a changing magnetic field in the conductor according to Faraday&rsquo;s law of induction. Eddy currents flow in closed loops within conductors, in planes perpendicular to the magnetic field.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41706,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Using the relation of magnetic susceptibility&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>&#967;</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and relative permeability<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>r</mi></msub></mfenced></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#967;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>99</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn></math></p><p>Magnetic permeability,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>r</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41710,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>80</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mT</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41715,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Hm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Hm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Hm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Hm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">m</mi></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>500</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Hm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41741,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math > <mn>3</mn></math>","<math> <mn>4</mn> </math>","<math> <mn>2</mn></math>","<math> <mn>1</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EM0025910_AnsExp_1.jpg\" style=\"width: 286px; height: 64px;\" /><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mtext>B</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mi>μ</mi> <mtext>o</mtext> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> <mi>π</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>M</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>x</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>&nbsp;for end-on position<br /><br /><math> <mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mover accent=\"true\"> <mi>M</mi> <mo stretchy=\"true\">→</mo> </mover> <mo>.</mo><mover accent=\"true\"> <mi>B</mi> <mo stretchy=\"true\">→</mo> </mover> </math><br /><br /><math> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mi>μ</mi><mi>o</mi></mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi></mrow> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn><msup> <mi>M</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mi>x</mi> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </math><br /><br /><math> <mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mi>d</mi><mi>U</mi></mrow> <mrow> <mi>d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mo>−</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>μ</mi><mi>o</mi></mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi></mrow> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn><msup> <mi>M</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mi>x</mi> <mn>4</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </math><br /><br />therefore force between them&nbsp;<math><mrow><mo>∝</mo> <msup> <mtext>x</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41755,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["are from north-pole to south-pole of the magnet","do not exist","depend upon the area of cross-section of the bar magnet","are from south-pole to north-pole of the magnet"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":41730,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0.007</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0.02</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0.014</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0.01</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>As we know that, work done in rotating a magnetic dipole in magnetic field is,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>M</mi><mi>B</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Now in the above given question we have, Magnetic Moment&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>,Magnetic Field<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>&nbsp;,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>rad</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>Let initial angle&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;so on reversing the direction of magnetic moment final angle&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>180</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></math></p><p>Now, substituting all the values in equation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;we get,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msup><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msup><mn>180</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>&#8757;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msup><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>and</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msup><mn>180</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>99</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p><p>Therefore, the work done in reversing the direction of the magnetic moment is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null}]